ws.</li>\n<li><strong>Representative Democracy</strong> is more common and involves electing officials to represent the people's interests. This system is prevalent in large, complex societies where direct participation is impractical.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Both forms share foundational elements such as free and fair elections, rule of law, separation of powers, and protection of minority rights. Yet, the implementation of these features can vary widely.</p>\n<h2>Key Features and Principles of Democracy</h2>\n<p>Understanding the characteristics that define democracy helps clarify its multifaceted nature. Some of these key features include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Political Participation:</strong> Citizens have the right and opportunity to vote, run for office, and engage in political discourse.</li>\n<li><strong>Majority Rule and Minority Rights:</strong> While majority decisions prevail, democracies protect minority groups from oppression.</li>\n<li><strong>Rule of Law:</strong> Laws apply equally to all citizens, including leaders, ensuring accountability and fairness.</li>\n<li><strong>Transparency and Accountability:</strong> Governments operate openly, and officials are answerable to the public.</li>\n<li><strong>Protection of Fundamental Rights:</strong> Freedom of speech, religion, assembly, and press are essential for democratic functioning.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>These principles create an environment where governance is not only about authority but also about ensuring that power serves the collective interests of society.</p>\n<h3>Democracy Compared to Other Forms of Government</h3>\n<p>To grasp what is democracy what is democracy fully, it is useful to contrast it with other political systems such as autocracy, oligarchy, and authoritarianism.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Autocracy</strong> centralizes power in the hands of a single leader or a small elite, often limiting political freedoms.</li>\n<li><strong>Oligarchy</strong> involves rule by a few individuals, typically 